  <h2 id="three-phase">How Three-Phase Separation Works</h2>
  <p>
    Conventional two-phase centrifuges separate a single liquid phase from suspended solids. The DMPX-014 is a true three-phase separator: it simultaneously processes a feed stream containing two immiscible liquids (for example, oil and water) plus suspended solid particles, producing three separate output streams in a single continuous pass.
  </p>
  <p>
    Inside the spinning bowl, centrifugal force stratifies the feed by density. The light liquid phase (oil, lower density) migrates inward and exits through the light-phase outlet. The heavy liquid phase (water or aqueous solution, higher density) migrates toward the bowl wall and exits through the heavy-phase outlet. Solid particles, being densest of all, accumulate at the bowl periphery and are ejected through hydraulically actuated discharge ports during programmed cleaning shots.
  </p>
  <p>
    This three-phase capability eliminates the need for separate oil-water separators and filter systems downstream of the centrifuge. One machine does what previously required multiple process steps.
  </p>

